## Feedback on Your "Linked List" Implementation

Your code is functional, but **it's not actually a linked list** — it's just a wrapper around a JavaScript array. This is a significant conceptual issue.

### What Makes a Linked List a Linked List

A linked list consists of **nodes**, where each node contains:
- A **value**
- A **pointer/reference** to the next node (and previous, for doubly-linked)

This structure gives linked lists their characteristic performance tradeoffs.

### Problems with Your Implementation

- **Uses an array internally** — you get array performance characteristics, not linked list ones
- **`remove(index)` uses splice** — this is O(n) array shifting, not O(1) pointer manipulation
- **No node structure** — there's no concept of nodes or pointers
- **Misleading abstraction** — callers think they're using a linked list but aren't

### A Genuine Implementation

```javascript
class Node {
    constructor(value) {
        this.value = value;
        this.next = null;
    }
}

class LinkedList {
    constructor() {
        this.head = null;
        this.size = 0;
    }

    add(value) {
        const node = new Node(value);
        if (!this.head) {
            this.head = node;
        } else {
            let current = this.head;
            while (current.next) {
                current = current.next;
            }
            current.next = node;
        }
        this.size++;
    }

    remove(index) {
        if (index < 0 || index >= this.size) return null;

        let removed;
        if (index === 0) {
            removed = this.head;
            this.head = this.head.next;
        } else {
            let current = this.head;
            for (let i = 0; i < index - 1; i++) {
                current = current.next;
            }
            removed = current.next;
            current.next = removed.next;
        }

        this.size--;
        return removed.value;
    }

    get(index) {
        if (index < 0 || index >= this.size) return null;

        let current = this.head;
        for (let i = 0; i < index; i++) {
            current = current.next;
        }
        return current.value;
    }
}
```

### Key Differences

| Operation | Your Version | Real Linked List |
|-----------|-------------|------------------|
| `add` | O(1) amortized | O(n) without tail pointer |
| `remove` | O(n) array shift | O(n) traversal, O(1) pointer update |
| `get` | O(1) | O(n) traversal |

### Suggestions for Further Improvement
- Add a **`tail` pointer** to make `add` O(1)
- Add **`prepend`** for true O(1) insertion at head
- Consider a **doubly-linked list** for O(1) removal with a node reference
- Add **iteration support** via `Symbol.iterator`

